	The Rules establish a sophisticated technological framework that transforms the general mandate of Section 40C into a functional monitoring system. Rule 150 ZQT  mandates monitoring through intelligent video surveillance and video analytics using approved equipment including video cameras, sensors, and related apparatus. The system requirements, as detailed in Rules 150 ZQX  and 150 ZQY , encompass high-definition video capture, object detection and counting capabilities, weighing functionality for bagged products, real-time data transmission to the Central Control Room (CCR), automated alarm generation for unauthorized production stoppages, and comprehensive data storage architectures with both local (60-day) and central (5-year) retention capabilities. This technological specification represents a deliberate implementation of the \"electronic or other means\" contemplated by Section 40C, creating an integrated system that provides the FBR with unprecedented real-time visibility into production activities while establishing clear technical standards for system implementation and operation.
	Section 50 of the Act of 1990 grants the FBR the power to “make rules for carrying out the purposes of this Act.” This is the general enabling provision for delegated legislation. More specifically, Section 40C of the Act of 1990 provides the particularized delegation for electronic monitoring, authoring the Board to “specify any registered person or class of registered persons or any good or class of goods” for monitoring through electronic means. Thus, the legal architecture is clear: Parliament (via Sections 50 and 40C) delegates the authority to the FBR. Similarly, section (8) of the Act of 2007 envisages that the FBR subject to certain conditions may delegate any of its functions and powers to any Government agency, Chairman or any member duly appointed under the Act. The FBR (via SRO 889(I)/2020) exercises that delegated power. In this regard, the worthy counsel representing the FBR has provided notification No.C.No.6(96)S(BIC)/Admn/2020 /23382-R, dated 16.02.2021. According to the said notification, the power of framing Rules under section 50(1) has been delegated to the Member Inland Revenue (Policy). The worthy counsel for the Revenue has also provided all the relevant record through detailed comments, showing that the proposed structure of installation of IP CCTV camera has been placed before the Member (Operations), who is the competent authority (delegated authority) under notification dated 16.02.2021 to issue the said directive. Nevertheless, such delegation does not amount to the essential legislative function of the Parliament; rather, it constitutes ancillary/incidental functions relating to the machinery provisions of a taxing statute, and therefore, does not fall within the prohibited field of delegation. This was very aptly observed by the apex Court in the case of Messrs Sh. Abdur Rahim, Allah Ditta vs. Federation of Pakistan and others (PLD 1988 SC 670) in the following terms:
“What is prohibited by the Legislature is the delegation of its function to make the law; but not the authority exercised under and in pursuance of eth law itself to another agency in regard to the provision of details when by the very nature these are incapable of being laid down by the legislature itself.”

150 ZQR. Application.- The provisions of this Chapter shall apply to video surveillance for electronic monitoring of production on real time basis, hereinafter referred to as the specified goods meant, namely:-
	(a) goods specified in Third Schedule appended to the Sales Tax Act, 1990; or
	(b) any other goods notified by the Board through a specific order:
		Provided that for any or all of the goods specified above shall be monitored through video surveillance and video analytics from the date as notified by the Board through a specific order.

 .	150 ZQT. Goods to be monitored electronically through video cameras etc- (1) Production of specified goods, manufactured in Pakistan, shall be monitored through intelligent video surveillance, and video analytics by installation of equipments including video cameras, sensors, etc., at production lines, as are approved by the Board for,-
(a) 	real time collection of data that shows production through object detection and object counting;
(b) 	transmission of data to central control room at FBR on real time basis, storage and archiving of data;
(c) 	detection of unexpected stops;
(d) 	quantitative analyses of productions; and
(e) 	data analytics for required legal actions.
	(2) No person engaged in manufacturing of specified goods shall remove the production from its business premises unless it has undergone the process of intelligent video surveillance.
 . 	150 ZQX. Criteria for grant of an authorization.- (1) The vendor shall be required to have and demonstrate ability to provide equipment with high security and efficiency for electronic monitoring of production and video analytics on real time basis.
	(2) 	The equipment offered by the vendor must have the following features, namely:-
(a) 	the equipment shall have high definition video camera and sensor that can record and count the production;
(b) 	the equipment shall have ability to weigh the product contained in bags;
(c)	the equipment shall have ability to integrate with the software recommended by FBR which will be used for transmission of data to central control room;
(d)	the equipment will conduct video analytics and communicate results thereof to 	CCR;
(e)	the equipment will report any unauthorized stoppages production through generation of appropriate alarm;
(f)		the system should have sixty days remotely retrievable local, on-site, and at place, specified by the Board, off-site, data storage at each site;
(g) 	the CCR should have a central data storage capacity capable of storing and retrieving data on long term basis up to five years; and
(h) 	the equipment must be stable, fault-tolerant, secure and accessible only by username and password as authorized by the Board.

 .	150 ZQY. Functions and responsibilities of IT team of FBR.-(1) IT team shall develop a software to run and operate the system, as per requirements of the Board. The equipment provided by the vendor after integration with FBR software shall be able to perform the following functions, namely:-
	(a) 	monitoring capability on real-time basis at factory premises or production lines;
	 (b)	the ability to configure the production unit remotely;
	(c)	the system must be capable of sending alert messages and trigger alarms, visible and audible, in case of occurrence of abnormal events such as 	unauthorized stoppages of production, tempering with equipments and camera 	etc;
	(d)	the system reporting should be capable to filter and process the production data 	for statistical and analytical purposes; and
	(e)	the system should ensure secure data storage and archiving of data for five years from its generation or recording;
	(2) The team shall submit a complete list of operations, software and maintenance required to operate the equipment.

a) Any inadequate care provided to a patient by a healthcare provider that results in harm or injury or worsens a pre-existing medical condition might qualify as a breach of the duty of care required of the healthcare provider in the given conditions and on the generally acceptable and applied standard. However, for it to qualify as criminal negligence, something more is required; the severity of harm and the degree of negligence has to be so high that it takes the conduct of the delinquent out of the bounds of mere ‘negligence’ into the realm of ‘gross negligence’ or ‘recklessness’.
b) In all professional negligence cases (not just medical/healthcare), the standard/test seems to be: what a reasonable, competent professional in the same field would do in similar facts and circumstances? This question can only be answered by a body of experts and until it is answered it cannot be said whether a doctor or any healthcare service provider has been negligent or even whether the death or harm has been caused due to his act or omission. Thus the causation or even actus reus constituting any offence cannot be determined. It is for this reason that the legislature decided to route the complaint of any aggrieved party through the Healthcare Commission and first determine the existence and extent of any negligence on part of the Healthcare service provider and then recommend the appropriate disciplinary, civil or criminal action(s) against the delinquent. This was done through the KP Health Care Commission Act, 2015 (‘Act of 2015’) and the Complaint Management Regulations made thereunder.
c) The KP Healthcare Commission Act, 2015 has established a specialized expert body, and has created a self-contained mechanism under section 13 of the Act for the investigation and adjudication of complaints against medical practitioners and establishments. A cornerstone of this legislative scheme is its overriding effect (section 33) and immunity (section 19), explicitly stated to supersede any contrary provision in any other existing law. This establishes a clear legal hierarchy, affirming the well-settled jurisprudential principle that a special law, crafted to govern a specific subject matter with expert precision, must prevail over general laws when there is a conflict. The ‘Act of 2015’ does not leave the procedure for redress to conjecture; it meticulously outlines the process. It provides a transparent and structured pathway for inquiry/investigation into allegations of medical negligence by a body possessing the requisite expertise.
d) Quite independent of any other reason, the legal effect of the enactment of ‘the Act of 2015’ is that it occupies, to the exclusion of all other laws, the field of negligence and malpractice in the area of Healthcare. So, where the allegation concerns acts/omissions of a healthcare provider ‘in the course of professional duties’, the complaint must first go to the Commission under section 13 of ‘the Act of 2015’; the police are not to bypass this statutory filter by directly registering an FIR, for instance under section 322 PPC, as in the instant case. Hence, the law is clear:
(i)	No FIR can be registered against a healthcare service provider or a healthcare institution on the allegations of malpractice or negligence except at the instance of the commission;
(ii)	Any person aggrieved of any malpractice or negligence by a healthcare service provider or institution may file a complaint u/s 13 of ‘the Act of 2015’ before the KP Healthcare Commission;
(iii)	It is the duty and responsibility of the commission to expeditiously and diligently pursue and take the complaint to its legal and logical conclusion, which may also, after due process, include lodging of FIR under the relevant provisions of PPC (including section 322);
(iv)	It therefore follows that any such FIR registered directly without first approaching the Healthcare Commission would be without lawful authority and liable to be quashed.
e) The existence of a tailored statutory remedy renders the concurrent use of the general criminal process impermissible. Consequently, to allow these proceedings to continue would violate the clear intent of the legislature and undermine the specialized regulatory system it created. Thus, the FIR and all subsequent proceedings stemming from it are unsustainable in law and required to be quashed.

> Evidence, in legal context entails existence or nonexistence of a fact proved in the court of law. However, to qualify as evidence, it must align with the provisions of the Evidence Act, even if it convinces the judge of its authenticity Islam, 2021
> Circumstantial evidence: According to the Ratanlal and Dhirajlal, the Law of Evidence, circumstantial evidence is a proof of pertinent facts from which one might deduce the presence of the facts at issue, or factum probandum, by a process of logical deduction (Ratanlal & Dhirajlal,2018)\'. In Islamic jurisprudence, this phenomenon can be traced back to the incident of Prophet Yousuf and his brothers narrated in the Holy Book in Surah Yousuf, verse 17
•Guiding principles for evaluating circumstantial evidence:
\"The conviction can only be made on the basis of circumstantial evidence, if it excludes all hypothesis of innocence of the accused The circumstantial evidence must be incompatible with that of the innocence of accused. It should be incapable of any explanation of any other reasonable hypothesis than that of guilt of accused. For proving a case through circumstantial evidence following four essentials are required:
(1)	Circumstances from which conclusion is to be drawn should be fully established;
(2)	All facts should be consistent with hypothesis;
(3)	Circumstances should be of a conclusive nature;
(4)	Circumstances should lead to moral certainty and actually, exclude every hypothesis but one proposed to be proved.\"
